; 1. Sessions
; 	â€¢	What it is:
; 	â€¢	A session stores user authentication state on the server (in memory, Redis, DB).
; 	â€¢	Client stores only a session ID in a cookie.
; 	â€¢	On each request, server validates session ID and retrieves user data.
; 	â€¢	Flow:
; 	1.	User logs in â†’ Server creates a session record.
; 	2.	Server sends session ID in a cookie.
; 	3.	On each request â†’ cookie is sent â†’ server checks session store â†’ identifies user.
; 	â€¢	Pros:
; 	â€¢	Secure (session data stays on server).
; 	â€¢	Easy to invalidate/logout.
; 	â€¢	Cons:
; 	â€¢	Doesnâ€™t scale well (needs sticky sessions or centralized session store).
; 	â€¢	Interview Quote:
; â€œSessions are server-side authentication. The client holds only a session ID, and the server validates it against its session store.â€





; 2. JWT (JSON Web Token)
; 	â€¢	What it is:
; 	â€¢	A stateless authentication mechanism.
; 	â€¢	Token is signed (not encrypted) with secret or private key.
; 	â€¢	Contains user claims (payload like userId, roles).
; 	â€¢	Structure:
;     header.payload.signature
;     â€¢	Header â†’ algorithm (HS256, RS256).
; 	â€¢	Payload â†’ user info (not sensitive like password).
; 	â€¢	Signature â†’ to verify authenticity.

; 	â€¢	Flow:
; 	1.	User logs in â†’ Server generates JWT and sends it to client.
; 	2.	Client stores it (localStorage, cookies, memory).
; 	3.	On every request â†’ client sends token in Authorization: Bearer <token>.
; 	4.	Server verifies signature â†’ if valid, trusts user.
; 	â€¢	Pros:
; 	â€¢	Stateless â†’ server doesnâ€™t store user sessions.
; 	â€¢	Works well with microservices & APIs.
; 	â€¢	Cons:
; 	â€¢	Hard to invalidate early (until token expiry).
; 	â€¢	Bigger token size.
; 	â€¢	Interview Quote:
; â€œJWTs are stateless, self-contained tokens with claims. The server verifies them via signature, no DB lookup required.â€






; 3. OAuth 2.0 (Basics)
; 	â€¢	What it is:
; 	â€¢	A protocol for delegated authorization, not direct authentication.
; 	â€¢	Example: â€œLogin with Google/GitHubâ€.
; 	â€¢	Instead of giving your password, you grant access via an authorization server.
; 	â€¢	Actors:
; 	1.	Resource Owner â†’ User.
; 	2.	Client â†’ App requesting access.
; 	3.	Authorization Server â†’ Issues tokens (e.g., Google, Facebook).
; 	4.	Resource Server â†’ API with user data.
; 	â€¢	Flow (Authorization Code Grant):
; 	1.	User clicks â€œLogin with Googleâ€.
; 	2.	Redirect to Google â†’ user logs in and consents.
; 	3.	Google redirects back with Authorization Code.
